{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c17ad9d-9d0c-4e07-978d-c9d1e0aa57dd","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't the right property for this. Here's what you need:\n\n**On iOS**, set the platform-specific `UseSafeArea` to `False` on your page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**On Android (.NET 9+)**, apps are edge-to-edge by default, but layouts still respect safe area insets. Set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view itself:\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n```\n\n**Also check** — if your page is inside a `NavigationPage` or `Shell`, the nav bar adds its own chrome. Hide it:\n\n```xml\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n<!-- or for Shell -->\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n```\n\n**Full example:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe two key pieces you were missing: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS, and `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the `Image` itself (not the page) for Android.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f4567c3c-c182-4abc-8350-891c4115c8c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. In .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to:\n\n1. Set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view (like the Image) itself, not just on the page\n2. Or use platform-specific APIs to handle the system bars\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe approach differs between iOS and Android—on iOS I'd use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` or the platform-specific `UseSafeArea=\"False\"`, while Android's edge-to-edge handling has evolved in recent .NET MAUI versions and may require different configuration depending on the version. I need to clarify the actual MAUI APIs here—`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard property. The real solution involves using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS to disable safe area handling, while on Android in .NET 9+, edge-to-edge rendering is enabled by default but the page still respects system insets unless explicitly configured otherwise. I should provide the correct platform-specific approach rather than working with non-existent properties.","outputTokens":1325,"requestId":"7FCF:70BC2:624A102:6B30F6F:69F159A6"},"id":"3ce172ea-aff9-4c7a-b4e4-a96f0b8346ad","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:07:09.493Z","parentId":"664088fb-9531-4a30-8258-b87b1f09a0ec"}
